  "text": "Cigarette smoking is the major risk factor for lung cancer, although additional factors have been identified [CITATION_1] . Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) may increase the risk of lung cancer. Metabolomic approaches were applied to distinguishing COPD and lung cancer in serum samples collected from patients with one of these diseases (TNM stages I, II, III, and IV). Higher levels of acetate, citrate, and methanol were found in individuals with COPD compared to those with lung cancer; and N-glycosylated proteins, leucine, lysine, mannose, and choline levels were higher in those with lung cancer [CITATION_2] .",
